translation:
One who is strong, consumes either boiled rice or barley soup, clarified butter or honey, or curd made from milk, in moderation at appropriate times, along with a small quantity of a drink;
Who is free from stiffness and excess flesh, and consumes jangala and shulya foods;
By knowing the time to use a kaphapraseka, one can counteract excess phlegm with warmth and lightness.
The practice that removes kapha through vomiting is praised, as it benefits the heart, digestion, and elimination.

Learn from this point onward the yoga methods that destroy madness,
With hingu, sauvarcala, usira, and dvipala, mixed with ghee in a pot;
Indeed, in the chant of four-syllabled cow mantra lies the success in suppressing madness.

Consisting of Haritaki, Katphala, Udumbara, Pathedi, Arjuna, Dhanvana, and Kadamba; as well as both Haridra and Tagara, Viḍaṇga, and Śālā-Arjuna;

And also Khadira, Dhava, Surā, Va Kuṣṭha, Aguru, and Candana;

Two and three Phalā, Sapāṭhā, Pathedi, Murvā, Śva-Daṃṣṭrā;

Yavani, Uśīra, Abhayā-Guḍūcī, Cavya, Ābhayā-Citraka, and sapta Parṇāḥ;

Presented in kaṣāyāḥ pādaiḥ, recommended for Kapha-Mehinām by ten upadiṣṭāḥ;

Infused with madhu, these samprayuktāḥ herbs are indeed a potent concoction.

[Verse 30:] Adorned with usheera, lodhras, kasthuri, and candana, which instill fearlessness in the minds of those who apply it; sweetened with patala, nimba, and malaka fruits that taste like nectar, and are adorned with fearlessness-granting lotus, padma, and vriksha kanya trees;

[Verse 31:] Adorned with lodhras grown in ambu, kali, yaka, dhataki plants, nimba and arjuna trees that are favorable for health, and with shirisha, sarja, and arjuna kesara resembling the color of gold, and adorned with priyangu, padma, utpala, and kimshuka flowers;

[Verse 32:] Adorned with asvattha, partha, and veta trees that are pure and sacred, having kaṭaṅka and kaṭeḥ flowers at their tops, praised by the wise ones, adorned with mustaka flowers; among these, ten types of mudras are prescribed for the feet, which when performed correctly, removes impurities and fills one's mind with sweetness.

Of haritaki, take half the measure, and of āmalaka likewise; add to it a tenth part of kapittha; then half of indravaruṇī;
In a quarter-droṇa, mix together viḍaṅga, pippalī, lodhram, and marica, a gram each, and twice that amount of śailavāluka.
To this, add half of the remaining juice of droṇa; then, in pure, cool water, soak guḍa for a hundred units of its own measure;
Of that, set aside a quarter for ghṛta-bhājana.
